audio engine for report:
    it receives data packet from communication polling thread.
    packet is comprised of start + fields.. + end.
    so it reads serial port char by char from a start char to end and then interprets the fields.
    it normalizes (to [0..1] float) and wires each value to a transformation/param in the audio generation.
    each transformation (param update) is published as an event (comprising of the type and the value) on the event ring buffer.
    the the main thread repeatedly runs datacallback.
    at each run of datacallback it pops every event, updates global state (that encapsulates those values) then updates the node graph with the new params.
    the nodes in the nodegraph (in this case a chain) generate sound batch of frames by batch of frames following their respective node_process_pcm_frames function and aplying the transoformation to every sample in the next batch to be played.
    notes play concurrently (each has their own adsr corresponding to the values that they had when note was initialized).
    each note represents the pitch corresponding to it's MIDI value + the offset.
    the volume of each note is 1 / n_active_notes as to keep volume always same.
    adsr is essentially a state machine with four stages that uses gain both as step and transformation to the audio source (gain * audio_sample_amp).
    when gain reaches a certain bound it switches stages and behaves differently. (attack -> ramp up all the way | decay -> ramp down slightly | sustain -> hold | release -> ramp down all the way)
    release starts at NOTE_RELEASED from whatever gain value the audio source was at the moment of release.
    lfo in practice is as a very low frequency in harmony with the rest of the frequencies playing (corresponding to the active notes), but it is so low that our brain interprets it as movement instead of sound.
    lfo output is a sine wave generated value between -1 and 1 and we multiply input audio frame amp by it.
